Hello Buckaroo Fans.

We are ready to begin selling online tickets for the first home Buckaroo Varsity Football Game. The game will be Friday night at Buckaroo Stadium beginning at 7:30pm.

Online tickets are on sale NOW! All ticket prices will be $5.00 plus online fees. All ages of children will need a ticket due to the need to meet the University Interscholastic League's requirement of 50% stadium capacity for both home and visitor fans.

In order to purchase an online ticket, please go to https://breckenridge.hometownticketing.com/embed/all

You may also access the Breckenridge ISD website for a link.

We encourage everyone to get tickets early, as availability may be limited later in the week due to capacity and social distancing requirements.

Season ticket holders can call the BISD Administration Office to get instructions on how to claim their prepaid tickets.

post_text: Replacing the field turf at Buckaroo Stadium was approved as part of the 2019-2020 budget in August. Demolition and removal of the old turf requires heavy equipment and was part of the contract with the installer. The value of any salvaged materials is included in the contract and belongs to the contractor. There is approximately 80,000 square feet of turf on the field. Including the sand and rubber pellets that infiltrate the plastic grass, each square foot weighs 3lbs. 240,000 lbs. of turf, sand, and rubber will have to be removed. Breckenridge ISD does not have the equipment to handle the removal nor does it have the manpower to piece mill the disposal of the turf. It was determined that the best value for the district was for the contractor to haul and dispose of the used turf.

Boosters, parents, sponsors...

Before any fundraising takes place on behalf of BISD students, this form must be completed and approved by the principal of the campus on which the students benefited reside. Example: If you are raising money for Class of 2022, those kids are in High School, so the form must go to the High School Principal for approval. If you are selling widgets for the Class of 2022 on the East Elementary campus, you must show the approved form to the East Elementary Principal and get her permission to sell widgets on that campus.

This form must be completed for all fundraising that takes place on BISD property or on behalf of BISD students or organizations.

On your mark...
Get set...
Go!

You may notice, especially around the Junior High and High School, entrances and gates that were previously open, may be closed. In an effort to improve safety and security, we have decreased the number of places people can enter, so that we can monitor them better. Please be understanding of these changes as they are meant to keep our kids safe.

The Junior High Main Entrance has been moved to the West end of the building. It has an electronic access camera and intercom system. If you need in the Junior High, come to the West Entrance to access the system.

Please note the changes to parking and traffic around the school for the upcoming school year. These parking hours will be in effect from 7:45-4:00 PM.

1. Student parking - all students with a pass (green and orange pass) may park in the front two lots across from the HS.

2. Seniors (green pass) may park in specific spaces designated in front of Bailey. Those spots will be drawn for. The first 15 seniors to purchase a pass this 6 weeks will get to park in front of Bailey...every other 6 weeks will be drawn for.

3. Athletes may move their vehicles to the concrete lot across from the Fine Arts/Athletic center at lunch.

4. Drop off/pickup - parent drop off and pick up must only occur in front of the HS, heading west.

5. Bus drop off/pick up - will happen in front of the Fine Arts Athletic Center.

6. The interior of campus will be closed to all traffic.

7. Parking in lots closer to band/Ag after hours is acceptable.

Thank you!

In an attempt to be more transparent with fundraising that goes on at school, we have developed the attached form which MUST be completed by any group raising money on behalf of BISD Students, organizations, or campuses. Any group doing fundraising that takes place on campus or results in a donation of funds, supplies, or equipment to the school or student group must complete this form and have it on file with the campus principal before the fundraising begins.

Please help us get this to the appropriate people, ASAP.

This does not apply to outside groups that do not raise money on district property and support activities that take place outside of school.

Breckenridge High School participates in the myCollegeOptions program which tracks kids' post-secondary education options. According to their data:

33.5% of our kids plan to pursue a Science, Technology, Engineering, or Math (STEM) career versus 26.1% nationally;

38.9% will be the first in their families to attend college; and

91.6% plan to attend a four-year institution.

stoves
refrigerators (CFS's must be removed and tagged)

construction debris, dead animals, hazardous waste, stable matter, chemicals, paints, thinner, tires, batteries, oil and oil filters, antifreeze, drums, asbestos, untreated medical wastes, contaminated soils, sludge, and automobile/truck engine parts.

Breckenridge North Elementary
February 22, 2019 at 10:59 AM ·

Dear Parents,

In this first week of our study on citizenship, we focused on respecting authority. The students learned what authority means and who authority figures are. Then went practiced real-life scenarios about respecting authority figures. Our students were not only taught that they should follow the rules and laws, but they should do it with a good attitude. You can further your child’s character learning by doing the following at home:
-Discussing who are authority figures in your household.
-Discussing who are authority figures in your life and how you handle authority as an adult.

Here is the definition of citizenship to review with your child:

Citizenship - Do your share to make your school and community better
Cooperate
Get involved in community affairs
Stay informed/vote
Be a good neighbor
Obey laws and rules
Respect authority
Protect the environment
volunteer

Have a great weekend!
Shannon Deen
BISD Counselor

Dear Parents,
This week we have concluded our study on being responsible. Our focus this week has been on thinking before you speak. The students should know that before they speak their words should be T-true, H-helpful, I-inspiring, N-necessary, K-kind. Next six weeks we will be looking into the character trait of Citizenship. Please help your child get a head start on next week's learning by reviewing the definition of Citizenship with him/her.
Citizenship -
1. Do your share to make your school and community better?
2. Cooperate
3. Get involved in community affairs
4. Stay informed, vote
5. Be a good neighbor
6. Obey laws and rules
7. Respect authority
8. Protect the environment
9. Volunteer

Have a marvelous weekend and see you on Tuesday!

Shannon Deen, Counselor

post_text: We have a higher than normal presence of law enforcement at the High School today. This morning we received a report of a threat, via some scribbling on a bathroom wall. Law enforcement were immediately called in and an investigation has been going on since then. At this time, there is no evidence that this threat is credible. Law Enforcement presence will remain high, and everyone will remain on a higher level of alert; however, we are carrying on with school activities. Please remember that at times like these, maintaining normality actually helps to identify when something is out of the ordinary. The threat was time specific and will expire tomorrow; however, law enforcement presence will be maintained. Thank you for your understanding as we take every precaution to keep our kids safe.

I have to brag on our Buckaroos for a minute...

In the past week I’ve received two positive reports from people outside of Breckenridge who were visiting our campus. They were very complimentary and said our students were kind and had excellent manners.

I was very proud to hear this, although I wasn’t surprised. It’s great to know we have a community that values citizenship and positive relationships. It speaks well to the future of our community...we’re in great hands moving forward. Great job, Bucks!

post_text: TAKE THE SURVEY!
shared_text:
Breckenridge ISD
October 1, 2018 at 11:09 AM ·

TAKE THE SURVEY!

Results so far show that different groups definitely have different priorities. Here is what these three groups have selected as their highest priority so far:

Students -- Creativity and Innovation
Teachers -- Personal Responsibility
Parents -- Academic Mindset

It's not too late to get in the game!

Breckenridge ISD is about to embark on a new endeavor; that is, to determine 'why' we exist. Of course, the short answer is because kids need to learn. But learn what? And how? And why? Has any of that changed in the last 100 years? Are we preparing our kids based on their future or our past? Are we raising up a generation that will help drive our community forward?

You are invited to complete this survey, in which you will be asked to select the most critical 21st century competencies our students need to prepare them to be successful lifelong learners and contributors in our complex, rapidly changing world.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeKJPqoRLfJY5_vL-Cq38xa9Fch_UXkT6wGCI9NOh0VVxRLiQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

text: #TogetherIsBetter

shared_text:
Breckenridge North Elementary
October 9, 2018 at 8:47 AM ·

Dear Parents,
This six weeks our students are learning the character trait respect. We have talked about how to treat others with respect and how we should treat others the way we want to be treated. We went into detail about the golden rule and why we should follow it. We also discussed that we should always think before we speak.
At home, please:
1. Have your child practice showing compassion to others.
2. As a family, plan and do an act of kindness over the weekends.
3. Discuss a time that you did not think before you spoke. What was the outcome? Did what you said hurt someone else? If so were you able to fix the relationship?
Review what respect means with your child:
1. Treat other with respect - Follow the Golden Rule (treat others the way you want to be treated)
2. Be tolerant and accepting of differences
3. Use good manners
4. Don’t use bad language
5. Never threaten, hit or hurt anyone
6. Be considerate of the feelings of others
7. Deal peacefully with anger, insults, and disagreements

Thank you!
Shannon Deen
BISD Counselor

shared_text:
Being a Better Breckenridge
October 2, 2018 at 11:11 AM ·

October is Clean the Curbs Month! Two Breckenridge Civic Organizations are teaming up this fall to keep downtown clean, even making it a contest to see whether the North or South side of Walker Street is kept cleanest.

Join in this effort to Clean the Curbs in Breckenridge by cleaning the curb at your place of business or residence and then help someone that cannot do it for themselves!

We will be posting pictures of curbs that are cleaned.

The city is having brush pick up this month, as well, so this is a good time to clean up the whole yard!

Share this with everyone you know in Breckenridge!

#TogetherIsBetter #CleanTheCurbsBreckenridge

New for Student Transportation:

We are using Route Numbers this year, instead of bus numbers. When we have to have a sub bus or when we get new buses, it is very confusing for everyone to change bus numbers. This way, your kid is assigned a Route. Your bus will have a Route Sign next to the door like the one in this picture. If you are on Route 2, no matter which particular bus is being used that day, the sign for your bus will read Route 2. It's simple really!

THE BRECKENRIDGE AMERICAN IS WRONG

Current Total School Tax Rate = $1.1685

Total School Tax Rate if the Tax Ratification Election Passes = $1.17 (Even though the voters are technically approving a tax rate of $1.30, the board has already taken action to reduce the I&S portion of the tax rate $0.13, so that the Total Tax Rate will be $1.17)This will result in the district receiving additional funds from the state of an estimated $270,000.

Total School Tax Rate if the Tax Ratification Election Fails = $1.17

$1.17-$1.1685 = $0.0015 That increase will happen whether the election passes or not. ($0.0015 , not $0.5315 like the Breckenridge American says. The article stating that Early Voting for the August 25 Election ends November 2 was incorrect, as well.)

Tax Increase on a $100,000 home resulting from $0.0015 tax increase is $1.50. And this increase will happen whether or not the TRE passes. (The tax increase noted in the paper is not accurate.)

Please Share!

Excerpt from Texas Association of School Administrators Article yesterday...

“We believe in a strong accountability system, but we ask this question: To whom should we be accountable and for what?’” said TASA Executive Director Kevin Brown. “School districts should be accountable to their local communities first, and the measures of accountability should represent the complex work that schools do to prepare children for the 21st century, including teaching innovation, leadership, critical thinking and real-world problem solving. Parents want their children to do rigorous, engaging work that sparks a lifelong love of learning, not prep for a multiple-choice test that colleges and businesses don’t even consider."

From THE EAGLE

Leon County voters back Oakwood school district tax swap

Voters in the Oakwood school district in Leon County overwhelmingly approved a "tax swap" during a special tax ratification election, or TRE, on Saturday.

According to officials, the process involves moving pennies from the interest and sinking side to the maintenance and operations side. By transferring the pennies, the district will be able to generate additional state funding without increasing the tax burden. The total tax rate remains $1.2444, but $70,000 to $80,000 in additional funds is expected to be generated.

"Finding strategic methods to increase school funding without asking our taxpayers to shoulder the cost is becoming harder each year," said Superintendent Donny Lee in an April press release announcing the initiative. More than half of all Texas school districts have passed TRE's, which demonstrates that communities support their children and public education."

From THE EAGLE, Bryan, Texas 77802

shared_text:
Breckenridge FFA
July 31, 2018 at 10:36 AM ·

Former Breckenridge High School Principal, Bryan Dieterich, was one of 8 outstanding school administrators honored at the Vocational Agriculture Teachers Association of Texas conference this morning. This award is in honor of exceptional achievements made by administrators who have made significant contributions to agriculture education.

Mr. D, as most of our students call him, was an agriculture teacher prior to his long running service as high school principal. As an administrator he could still recite the FFA creed and taught students the significance of the Lonestar degree. His support of BHS Ag teachers and FFA members has promoted student leadership through agriculture and has grown the BHS FFA program to one of the best in the state of Texas. Our hats off to you Mr. D! Thank you for your support.

Breckenridge High School
Breckenridge ISD
BISD Journalism & Web Media
